---
title: "Electrodynamics Today"
year: 1978
abstract: >
  The question whether Quantum Optics can provide any new evidence that
  might clear up the then outstanding difficulties in QED was raised at
  the 1966 Rochester Coherence Conference, in the author's talk
  entitled, "Is QED Necessary?" This was done in a deliberately
  provocative way because of a complacency in the air that tended to
  regard Quantum Optics as nothing more than an application of
  completely established theory. If this field has no long-range goals
  of its own relating to fundamental physics, it must inevitably
  degenerate into a kind of Engineering Service Facility, whose main
  function is to provide bigger and better lasers for use in other
  fields.
